<p>Keynes’s understanding of the castle-in-the-air theory made him a fortune. His process was as follows: Because no one can know with any certainty the future revenues or dividends of a given stock, <strong>he invested based on what he thought <em>other investors </em>would value</strong>. For example, if he sensed there was prevailing optimism in a certain sector of the economy, say in steel production, he would invest in steel companies regardless of their underlying fundamentals, simply because he anticipated other investors would soon rush into steel.</p>
